==English==

===Alternative spellings===
*[[ta-ta]], [[ta tah]], [[ta-tah]], [[tah tah]], [[tah-tah]]

===Etymology===
Probably derived from baby talk c1823 (imitative)

===Pronunciation===
{{IPAchar|[[t]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ɑː]]}}{{IPAchar|[[t]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ɑː]]}} or {{IPAchar|[[t]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ə]]}}{{IPAchar|[[t]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ɑː]]}} or {{IPAchar|[[t]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ə]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ˈ]]}}{{IPAchar|[[t]]}}{{IPAchar|[[ɑː]]}}

===Interjection===
'''ta ta'''

# ''informal:'' [[goodbye]]
#*'''1923:''' Ed Smith of Cranbrook Courier, ''Reminiscences of Kootenay Pioneers'' (recalling an event claimed to be the origin of the place name '''''Ta Ta''' Creek'' recorded in 1900; viewed in British Columbia archives at [http://srmwww.gov.bc.ca/bcgn-bin/bcg10?name=17664]) - Red put the spurs to his horse and galloped away: "'''Ta ta''', friends, I've business up the trail."
#*'''2006:''' Daily Flute (blog) read at [http://dailyflute.com/?p=1031] on [[13 May]] [[2006]], '''''Ta ta''''' - I’m going to stop blogging, probably for good.

